In article <CG9Gps.Eys@Colorado.EDU> bear@tigger.cs.colorado.edu writes:

>Why would they want a truly random source?  Stream ciphers require that
>the same "random" sequence be known at both ends of the link; something
>not possible with a realtime hardware random source.

A random source is needed in Diffie-Hellman key exchange, which is
done before any Clipper encrypted data is sent.  This process
involves both parties in a conversation generating a random number
which is used to establish a common key.

To save bandwidth here, see the FAQ.

Andrew.
